To transform a context menu into a regular menu that shows on button press, you could do the following:

1. Create a menu resource file (e.g. `menu_main.xml`) and define your menu items in it using the `<item>` tag. For example:

```
<menu xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android">
    <item
        android:id="@+id/action_sort_title"
        android:title="Sort by Title" />
    <item
        android:id="@+id/action_sort_year"
        android:title="Sort by Year" />
</menu>
```

2. In your activity or fragment, override the `onCreateOptionsMenu()` method and inflate your menu resource file using the `MenuInflater` class. For example:

```
override fun onCreateOptionsMenu(menu: Menu): Boolean {
    menuInflater.inflate(R.menu.menu_main, menu)
    return true
}
```

3. Next, define the logic to handle menu item clicks in the `onOptionsItemSelected()` method. For example:

```
override fun onOptionsItemSelected(item: MenuItem): Boolean {
    return when (item.itemId) {
        R.id.action_sort_title -> {
            // handle sort by title
            true
        }
        R.id.action_sort_year -> {
            // handle sort by year
            true
        }
        else -> super.onOptionsItemSelected(item)
    }
}
```

4. Finally, attach a click listener to your button and call the `openOptionsMenu()` method to show the menu on button press. For example:

```
myButton.setOnClickListener {
    openOptionsMenu()
}
```

With these steps, you should now have a regular menu that shows on button press instead of a context menu.

