To parse the exported .rgl file, you will need to write your own code to read the file format. The .rgl file format is a custom file format used by rayGUILayout, and there is no pre-built parser for it in the raylib library.

Here is an example of how you could parse the .rgl file and create the required GUI controls using the raylib-cpp library:

```cpp
#include "raylib-cpp.hpp"
#include <string>

int main() {
    raylib::Window w(800, 600, "My App with GUI");
    raylib::GuiLoadStyle("resources/raygui/ricons_dark.png");
    raylib::GuiLoadStyle("resources/raygui/raygui.sty");

    // First, load the contents of the .rgl file into an std::string
    std::ifstream input("resources/gui/main_menu.rgl");
    std::string contents((std::istreambuf_iterator<char>(input)), std::istreambuf_iterator<char>());

    // The .rgl file contains a serialized version of the GUI controls, so we need to deserialize it
    raygui::ControlData data = raygui::DeserializeControlData(contents);

    // Now we can loop through the control data and create the corresponding GUI controls using raylib-cpp
    for (raygui::Control &control : data.controls) {
        switch (control.type) {
            case raygui::ControlType::BUTTON: {
                raylib::Button button("Button!");
                button.setPosition(control.bounds.x, control.bounds.y);
                button.setSize(control.bounds.width, control.bounds.height);
                // Set any other control properties as needed
                // ...
                break;
            }

            // Repeat for other control types (LABEL, TEXTBOX, etc.)
        }
    }

    while (!w.shouldClose()) {
        w.beginDrawing();
        raylib::DrawFPS(10, 10);
        // Draw your GUI controls here
        // ...
        w.endDrawing();
    }

    return 0;
}
```

Note that this example only demonstrates how to create `Buttons`, but you will need to repeat the code for each type of control that is used in your .rgl file. You will also need to adjust the control properties to match those used in your .rgl file.

